 with \"sausage fest\" with immediate effect. The Conservative party is many things, but on its period it is not – how could it be?</p><p>\"Sausage fest\" is a far more fitting term. Indeed, sausage was one of the first nouns I actually heard used in relation to the coalition government, as I awoke, head pounding, on the morning of Friday, 7 May 2010. I gained consciousness that spring morning to the plummy sounds of Boris Johnson's chilling statement that <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8668036.stm\" title=\"\">\"the meat in the [coalition] sausage has to be Conservative</a>\". Jeremy Paxman gamely continued with this macho analogy, inquiring as to whether it might be said to be a chipolata or a cumberland. Yes: the first event I witnessed when waking to the dawn of a new political era involved two privileged, middle-aged white men making phallocentric jokes on national television. Start as you mean to go on, guys.</p><p>But then we're fascinated by political sausages, aren't we? Just look at the top stories of the past few weeks. First we're told that François Hollande's been making a pig's ear of it with a younger woman behind the French first lady's back, then Liz Hurley's rumoured ex Tom Sizemore (a more fitting name for inclusion in this column is surely not possible) momentarily conned showbiz gossip mongers everywhere by alleging that she and Bill Clinton had had a private-jet-based affair. It <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/10621303/Liz-Hurley-and-Bill-Clinton-affair-was-all-made-up-admits-Tom-Sizemore.html\" title=\"\">turned out to be rubbish</a>, of course, but not before some pretty blue fan fiction had appeared online imagining the tryst in great detail. It shows how the power-is-an-aphrodisiac narrative still captivates us. Hurley's <a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/liz-hurley-denies-yearlong-affair-with-bill-clinton-after-sensational-us-media-reports-9109384.html\" title=\"\">2010 comments</a> on Cameron and Clinton (\"I think he's gorgeous. Super-sexy!\" she said of the former, adding: \"Powerful folk can be sexy … I adore Clinton\") were wheeled out as evidence of her status as politician shagger extraordinaire. Never mind that the story was bunkum – it cemented people's existing preconceptions about 21st-century gender roles.</p><p>And let's not forget <a href=\"http://www.vanityfair.com/society/2014/03/wendi-deng-note-tony-blair\" title=\"\">Vanity Fair's allegations</a> that Wendy Deng, ex-wife of Rupert Murdoch, has been lusting over ripped war criminal and hunk of meat Tony Blair. It's cringe-making stuff, to be sure. And yet, where powerful men are concerned, there's an expectation there that they will have attractive, nubile women lusting after them. This is a society in which the apparent existence of an archetypal power dynamic between a man and a woman still garners more media exposure than any female politician. Furthermore, unless a lady politician is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/09/should-mps-reality-tv-shows-penny-mordaunt-splash\" title=\"\">sporting a swimsuit on national television</a>, male politicians' wives are considered far more interesting, whether it's because they typify a demure, composed feminine archetype (SamCam) or appear to reject it (Sally Bercow). Indeed, the <a href=\"http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/cristinaodone/100258140/sally-bercows-latest-scandal-means-john-bercow-has-to-go/\" title=\"\">\"get your wife under control\" tone</a> to reporting about Bercow makes me sick to my stomach.</p><p>\"I'm more than just a dress,\" <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2431155/Labour-Party-Conference-2013-Ed-Miliband-Justine-Thorntons-cheesy-photo-stunts.html\" title=\"\">said Justine Thornton</a> at the Labour party conference last year, foreshadowing the party's renewed emphasis on issues of gender equality. Not in this country, I'm afraid, Justine, but still, you have a better chance than you would in the Tory party. As David Cameron desperately tried to point out at PMQs, they may have had some ham, once, in the form of Margaret Thatcher, but they're still just a bunch of male chauvinist porkers, and many of us are sick of sausages. In fact, I wish all the little piggies would just stay at home. It's time for some nut roast.</p>","headline":"I'm sick of politics being a sausage fest","trailText":"<strong>Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett: First thoughts:</strong> The 'women problem' identified by Ed Miliband goes wider than the Tory frontbench. Wives and lovers get more attention than female politicians","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mg6a","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391687981527/Boris-Johnson-with-David--001.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391687981527/Boris-Johnson-with-David--001.jpg","wordcount":"702","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429055233","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8652423","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-07T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039185","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T12:15:25Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/politics-sausage-fest-ed-miliband-tory-frontbench","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/politics-sausage-fest-ed-miliband-tory-frontbench","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/series/first-thoughts","webTitle":"First thoughts","type":"series","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/series/first-thoughts","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/seri