www.theguardian.com/profile/stevebell","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/profile/stevebell","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/g2/puzzles","webTitle":"Puzzles and cartoon","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2/puzzles","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2/puzzles","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/g2","webTitle":"G2","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2","references":[]},{"id":"type/cartoon","webTitle":"Cartoon","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/cartoons/archive","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/type/cartoon","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","references":[]}],"references":[],"elements":[{"id":"gu-image-428992430","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391617124050/Steve-Bells-If---06.02.20-004.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Steve Bell","photographer":"Copyright Steve Bell 2014/All Ri","altText":"Steve Bell's If … 06.02.2014","height":"203","credit":"Copyright Steve Bell 2014/All Ri/Steve Bell","caption":"Steve Bell's If ? 06.02.2014","width":"620"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-428992431","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391617119968/Steve-Bells-If---06.02.20-001.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Steve Bell","photographer":"Copyright Steve Bell 2014/All Ri","altText":"Steve Bell's If … 06.02.2014","height":"84","credit":"Copyright Steve Bell 2014/All Ri/Steve Bell","caption":"Steve Bell's If … 06.02.2014","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Sport, music, politics: they all need mavericks like Kevin Pietersen | Martin Kettle","webPublicationDate":"2014-02-06T06:01:00Z","sectionName":"Comment is free","sectionId":"commentisfree","id":"commentisfree/2014/feb/06/sport-politics-music-mavericks-kevin-pietersen","fields":{"standfirst":"The batsman's brilliance proved too much for England. But like Maria Callas or Winston Churchill he was an essential talent","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-02-06T09:53:13Z","body":"<p>How do you solve a problem like Kevin?&nbsp;Not this way, in my view. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/04/kevin-pietersen-england-ecb\" title=\"\">England cricket's announcement this week that&nbsp;it prefers to cut&nbsp;its best player adrift</a> rather than endure any more of the dressing-room divisions and on-field&nbsp;frustrations that appear to be&nbsp;part of the package deal that is Kevin&nbsp;Pietersen seems a clear sign of official weakness not strength. Problem solved? In my view it's a problem ducked and problem failed.</p><p>For those of you who neither know nor care about England cricket, rest assured that this column is only briefly and metaphorically about sport. Really it's about genius, or at least about special, sometimes awkward, brilliance. Its theme is that the problem posed to English cricket by Pietersen's reckless talent – and the safety-first way it has been bundled out of the room – has resonances that are much wider than sport.</p><p>It's pretty obvious from beyond the boundary that Pietersen has an Everest-size ego, is absurdly cavalier with his talent, and frequently puts himself first, rather than the team. Yet on his day Pietersen is still the most exciting English batsman of the last decade and one of the most talented of all time. He hasn't played well in Australia this winter – though he still got <a href=\"http://stats.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2013-14/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=7899;type=series\" title=\"\">more runs than any other England player</a>. But the fact that he also appears to be a pain in the backside means he has been made the fall guy for failure. Now he's gone, and we are the poorer for it.</p><p>These dilemmas can occur in all walks of life, but cricket has handled its version in exactly the wrong way. Writing yesterday, for instance, under the headline \"Master of his art always worth the trouble\" the Times's Simon Barnes compared Pietersen with Deco in The Commitments. Everyone in the band disliked Deco because he was a pain, he wrote. But Deco had a great voice, and the band was nothing without him. As Barnes put it: \"He made&nbsp;the band and he destroyed the band. Or perhaps the band destroyed themselves because they couldn't face the fact that they needed him.\"</p><p>The performing arts, with their larger than life diva personalities, are full of such examples. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Callas\" title=\"\">Maria Callas</a> was simply the best of most eras. She&nbsp;set new standards of intensity. There has&nbsp;been no one to touch her since she&nbsp;gave&nbsp;up in&nbsp;the early 1960s. But Callas was a monster as well as a marvel. She threw&nbsp;tantrums. She put herself first.&nbsp;She walked away mid-performance. She&nbsp;cancelled. She drove colleagues mad. But I'll go to my grave regretting that I am just too young to have heard Callas sing.</p><p>There is, admittedly, a fine line between the indispensable and the dispensable, and it makes a lot of difference which side of it you are on. In&nbsp;1919 the incomparably revered Italian&nbsp;conductor <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arturo_Toscanini\" title=\"\">Arturo Toscanini</a>, famous for <a href=\"http://fonderiausa.com/toscanini-in-a-rage\" title=\"\">his rages</a> with orchestras that failed to meet his standards, was so enraged by the sloppiness of a violin player in the Turin orchestra during a rehearsal that he jabbed at the man's bow with his conductor's baton. The bow went into the violinist's eye and the violinist sued. Toscanini won the case because the Italian courts accepted an expert witness's assertion that the Maestro was in a condition of \"sublime frenzy\" caused by his genius. Maybe Pietersen's lawyers should try that one on the England cricket board.</p><p>The American soprano <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathleen_Battle\" title=\"\">Kathleen Battle</a>, by contrast, was a top of the range star in the 1980s and early 1990s. Not a Toscanini or a Callas (who is?) but pretty good all the same. But Battle's ego and demands – she is said to have phoned her agent in New York from a limousine in California to get him to call the driver to turn down the air conditioning – seriously damaged her career. Managements <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/08/arts/the-met-drops-kathleen-battle-citing-unprofessional-actions.html\" title=\"\">sacked her</a>. Delighted stagehands at the New York Met sported T-shirts saying I Survived the Battle.</p><p>Politics has its equivalent of the Pietersen problem too – and it is sometimes even expressed in cricketing metaphors. Who can forget the <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/1/newsid_2513000/2513953.stm\" title=\"\">resignation speech by Sir Geoffrey Howe in 1990</a>, in which he excoriated Margaret Thatcher as a captain who had deliberately broken her&nbsp;team's bats in the changing room? There is a lot in common between the way Thatcher behaved, especially in her later career – undermining colleagues, picking fights, ignoring others and generally doing her own thing – and the problems that Pietersen is said to have caused in the England dressing room.</p><p>Like cricket, politics is a team game played by individuals who are preoccupied with their own success, to the extent of actively trying to do down those on their own side. In modern politics, where the insistence on being on-message and sticking to the line is such a dominant part of the culture, there is even less opportunity for a Pietersen to prosper than there once was. And where someone breaks the on-message rules, the consequences can be catastrophic. Australian Labor's&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Rudd\" title=\"\">Kevin Rudd</a>, determined to destroy the band because it had fired him, is a classic example.</p><p>But in politics, as in cricket, there needs to be space for the person whose&nbsp;talents outweigh the difficulties they occasionally cause. Winning teams&nbsp;need their mavericks like Kenneth Clarke, David Davis, Tom Watson or Frank Field – people who approach the conventional political arena from an unusual angle.</p><p>In British politics, the ultimate Pietersen was Winston Churchill,&nbsp;manifestly the best political leader of his era when the chips were down, but often a loner, an exile, and a difficult person to rein&nbsp;in or follow. \"When&nbsp;Winston was born,\" Stanley Baldwin confided in 1936, \"lots&nbsp;of fairies&nbsp;swooped down on his cradle with&nbsp;gifts – imagination, <sup></sup>eloquence, industry, ability – and then&nbsp;came a fairy&nbsp;who said 'No one person has a right&nbsp;to so many gifts' and picked him up and gave him such a shake and twist that with all these gifts he was denied judgment and wisdom.\" That's pretty much what the cricket writers have been saying about Pietersen this week, in fact.</p><p>But it wasn't Baldwin's last word on Churchill. \"I had the great pleasure of spending nearly three hours with Churchill in London yesterday,\" Baldwin wrote in 1943. \"You can take it from me he is a really big man, the war has brought out the best that was in him. I pray he is spared to see us through.\" Pietersen is no Churchill, of&nbsp;course. But in sport, as in politics, if&nbsp;you have a really big man available, you surely need him in your team.</p>","headline":"Sport, music, politics: they all need mavericks like Kevin Pietersen","trailText":"<p><strong>Martin Kettle:</strong> The batsman's brilliance proved too much for England. But like Maria Callas or Winston Churchill he was an essential talent</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"31","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mfmp","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391625114734/Kevin-Pietersen-at-the-Ov-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391625114734/Kevin-Pietersen-at-the-Ov-006.jpg","wordcount":"1064","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429001683","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8648790","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Martin Kettle","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-06T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2038903","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T06:01:00Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/sport-politics-music-mavericks-kevin-pietersen","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/sport-politics-music-mavericks-kevin-pietersen","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"sport/kevin-pietersen","webTitle":"Kevin Pietersen","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/kevin-pietersen","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/kevin-pietersen","references":[]},{"id