totally outside their control, but is that much different from the local car manufacturers having to deal with a sustained high dollar and, er … <a href=\"http://www.scribd.com/embeds/190829491/content?start_page=1&amp;view_mode=scroll&amp;access_key=key-2m5w1objvjalmfsdwru4\">minimal tariff protection</a>?</p><p>Aside from the location of their operations, what is the difference between workers on the Holden and SPC factory lines? Not a great deal. “But think of the farmers!” I hear you cry. “They’re the salt of the earth. They run <a href=\"http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/Lookup/4102.0Main+Features10Dec+2012\">family businesses</a>. And they made our nation what it is today.”</p><p>Yes, that’s true. But the mining industry also made Australia what it is today. And the services sector. And our defence forces. The fact that Australian farms are <a href=\"http://www.nff.org.au/farm-facts.html\">almost entirely</a> family owned and operated should not make them a protected species. Plenty of other unviable family businesses go to the wall in Australia and farm businesses shouldn’t be sacrosanct.</p><p>Food security is another red herring dangled in defence of our agricultural brethren. Yet Australian farmers currently supply 93% of the food we eat and still have two thirds of their produce left to <a href=\"http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/Lookup/4102.0Main+Features10Dec+2012#What%20are\">export</a>. So we’re <a href=\"http://www.politifact.com.au/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/may/17/bob-katter/within-three-eight-years-australia-will-be-net-imp/\">not facing any imminent risk</a> of having to depend on other nations for food, even if some of the 300,000 farming jobs are lost. </p><p>We do however import more processed fruit and vegetables than we export, which is why food-processing companies like SPC Ardmona are under pressure from foreign competitors with cheaper input costs. As are the local car manufacturing industry, and the textiles, clothing and footwear sector, just to name two other examples.</p><p>The real reason farm jobs are treated as a special case is because they have a parliamentary cheer squad: a casual trawl through the register of pecuniary interests shows the <a href=\"http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Members/Register\">members</a> and <a href=\"http://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Senators_Interests/Register\">senators</a> who also run family farms and earn additional income from their businesses, however modest that income might be. </p><p>Owning and operating a farm doesn’t appear to preclude these parliamentarians from agricultural committees or inquiries that might pose a conflict of interest – indeed a commercial interest could be said to be an apparent prequalification. It’s extraordinary that no other part of the Australian economy is similarly represented in parliament with such potential vested interests – other than the dinosaur and Titanic-restoration industries of course.</p><p>The simple fact is that farm businesses made unviable by weather, interest rates, the dollar, tariffs, or labor costs should no more be propped up by government than any other unsustainable business. Even the government’s own rural <a href=\"http://www.daff.gov.au/agriculture-food/drought/assistance\">assistance measures</a> seem to recognise this by focusing on preparedness and risk-management for farms under stress. </p><p>While Stone’s crash through or crash performance was certainly diverting, her neighbour in the adjoining electorate of Indi also made an interesting contribution to the SPCA debate yesterday. Drawing on her expertise as an agricultural consultant, whose role is to advise farmers on the best ways to run their operations, independent MP Cathy McGowan refrained from condemning the SPCA decision and opted instead to call for a \"<a href=\"http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/news/politics/indi-mp-cathy-mcgowan-supports-mining-magnate-mp-clive-palmer/story-fnkerdda-1226817548860\" style=\"font-size: 15px;\">national debate about what's the future for manufacturing for rural and regional Australia</a>.”</p><p>Stone is rallying for hearts, while McGowan is appealing to minds. It will be interesting to see which of the two parliamentarians’ remonstrations ultimately prevail.</p>","headline":"Australian farmers should not be treated like protected species","trailText":"<b>Paula Matthewson: </b><i></i>The fact that Australian farms are almost entirely family owned and operated should not make them a special case more worthy of government assistance than other professions","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mgv2","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391646119491/c5d80740-7703-49f8-8954-de5cdc48ad4a-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391646119491/c5d80740-7703-49f8-8954-de5cdc48ad4a-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"675","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429020394","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52f2c6efe4b0ab978b0f9720","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Paula Matthewson","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-05T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039015","productionOffice":"AUS","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T11:30:32+11:00"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/australian-farmers-should-not-be-treated-like-protected-species","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/06/australian-farmers-should-not-be-treated-like-protected-species","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardian