Title":"Stage-managed PMQs? The problems go deeper than that | Ally Fogg","webPublicationDate":"2014-02-05T18:02:10Z","sectionName":"Comment is free","sectionId":"commentisfree","id":"commentisfree/2014/feb/05/stage-managed-pmqs-problems-deeper-david-cameron","fields":{"standfirst":"The revelation that David Cameron's staff have been planting questions should signal the end of this grotesque charade","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-02-05T19:50:42Z","body":"<p>David Cameron has been attempting to stage-manage prime minister's questions, <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10617436/David-Camerons-attempts-to-stage-manage-Prime-Ministers-Questions.html\" title=\"\">according to a report today</a>. Leaked documents show that Gavin Williamson, the prime minister's parliamentary private secretary, has been sending a circular email around his backbenchers at about 11am every Wednesday, with a list of suggested \"free hits\" they could ask at midday.</p><p>The revelation comes shortly after John Bercow, the speaker, warned that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/02/speaker-john-bercow-control-mps\" title=\"\">soundbites and planted questions</a> have helped to damage the reputation of parliament in the eyes of the public. Really, John? On behalf of the public, let me suggest that the problems go a little deeper than that.</p><p>On the spectrum of stage-managed spectacles, one is tempted to place PMQs somewhere between a Punch and Judy show, a pantomime and a farce. This would be a great injustice. Those noble theatrical traditions have brought joy, laughter and colour into our lives for centuries; PMQs has brought nothing but shame and disgrace. The weekly performance is an embarrassment, the nadir of our anachronistic, elitist, dysfunctional parliamentary system.</p><p>I despise the ritual and the disingenuous cheek of the non-question: \"Does the prime minister have any plans to visit my home town in the near future, and if so would he care to observe the excellent new one-way traffic system we have installed in my constituency?\" The non-answer is worse. I long for a prime minister to reply: \"I'm sorry to inform the honourable gentleman that his constituency is by all accounts a rancid, concrete cesspit that is crawling with barbarians, heathens, oiks and riff raff and I'd sooner submit to root canal surgery than accept his generous offer.\"</p><p>Many observers point to the subhuman howling, braying and barking of the soundtrack as the worst feature of PMQs. In truth, I could just about tolerate that if it were accompanied by some authentic, animalistic hatred, meaning and purpose. I want my politicians to loathe each other. Too often, what we hear is not the explosion of righteous outrage but the ritualistic, synthetic foley  effects to a tedious, role-playing game, a tokenistic hear-hear-harr-harr-huh-huh-rhubarb. As Macbeth called life itself, a tale told by an idiot, full of sound and fury, signifying nothing.</p><p>Parliamentary correspondents and the professional political media love the occasion, of course. It is five minutes of guaranteed filler for the evening news or their weekly columns, with the performances of the prime minister and leader of the opposition reviewed and rated as if they were prizefighters, complete with descriptions of antagonists \"landing a few blows\" and \"throwing jabs\", when professional wrestling would be a more appropriate metaphor. It provides an easy narrative of winners and losers, a weekly opportunity for all the players, including those in the galleries, to feel like they are part of something that matters, something that counts.</p><p>They are kidding themselves. The Romans talked of bread and circuses as the key to keeping the plebs placated. PMQs affects to be politics, but in truth it is the biggest circus of all, a diversionary charade performed to convince us that we are being governed by a democratic process. When was the last time a point was made or a question was asked during PMQs that went on to influence and affect political administration? I'd hazard a confident guess that the answer is never.</p><p>As Douglas Adams noted long ago, a politician is a professional entertainer whose job is to distract the masses so the people who actually run the world can go about their business in peace. Nowhere is this writ larger than PMQs. Members of parliament can do a good job of holding power to account, at times. It occasionally happens with a speech in the chamber – think of the resignations of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/dec/31/heseltine-thatcher-westland-cabinet-meeting\" title=\"\">Michael Heseltine over Westland</a> or <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/apr/06/greatest-speeches-in-parliament-of-the-past-100-years\" title=\"\">Robin Cook over Iraq</a> – but more often in the backrooms of parliament. Consider how Tom Watson and the culture, media and sport committee painstakingly unpicked <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/phone-hacking\" title=\"\">the phone-hacking scandal</a>, for example. Such historic moments simply cannot happen at PMQs.</p><p>Bercow says he would like to consider prime minister's questions as a shop window on the work of the Commons. It is a forlorn hope. PMQs does not just demonstrate British parliamentary democracy at its worst; it represents everything that is wrong with it. If we are ever to transform the Palace of Westminster from a 17th-century public school debating club into a functional, modern seat of government, then this grotesque ritual has to be the first thing to go.</p>","headline":"Stage-managed PMQs? The problems go deeper than that","trailText":"<strong>Ally Fogg:</strong> The revelation that David Cameron's staff have been planting questions should signal the end of this grotesque charade","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p